felix fortunatumque esset, praefabantur. 41. euenat. One of the short subjunctive forms used by Plautus

only at the end of the line. Others are aduenat (Pseud. 1030), peruenat (Rud. 626), also pemcenant v. 93 and euenant (Epid. 321). These are properly aorist forms and are used by the dramatic poets only under metrical necessity. So the aorist forms attigas, attulas &c- usually (but not always) occur at the end of the line. See Lindsay, L. L.‚ pp. 464, 465. Note that euenire is used with adj. (bona &c.) not with adv, So often in the historians, because euenire almost =fierz2

42. teque. The force of uenerare is continued ‘and pray that I may see you &c.' Callicles has now turned away from his wife and speaks these words so that she should not overhear them.
